Where two beams connect at an upright, the beam connectors should remain reasonably parallel. If racking is overloaded or has occurred previously, the beam connectors will form a `Vâ€™. This is a quick and easy guide
Check for obvious signs of beams being hit by a pallet or forklift. Damaged beams must be replaced where the damage exceeds allowable tolerances

question.title: Are beam connectors correctly seated in the upright?

answer.text: Examine beams to ensure that the beam connectors are fully seated in the upright

question.title: Are safety clips in place in all beam connectors?

answer.text: Safety clips prevent beams from being accidentally dislodged. If the racking design includes safety clips, then a ll connectors must have a safety clip of the correct size and type correctly fitted

question.title: Are drive-in rack pallet support brackets damaged?

answer.text: Examine pallet support brackets for damage or twisting

question.title: Are drive-in rack pallet support rails damaged?

answer.text: Check pallet support rails for impact damage or flattening at the returns. Also check that bolts attaching the rail to the support brackets are tight and not damaged

question.title: Are pallets fully retained on pallet rails?

answer.text: Is the clearance between the rails sufficiently close enough to prevent pallets falling between the rails?

If an upright shows significant damage, or is twisted or contains splits or cracks, then replace it or splice a new section in. If the upright is damaged and is to be replaced, the footplate must be inspected as it may also have sustained damage

Check the condition of any splices. They must be free from damage or cracks and be above the first beam level; i.e. not close to the ground where they take most of the weight. If uprights are joined with welds check the condition of the welds to ensure the weld is not cracking
Replace bent horizontal or diagonal braces. For bracing, the member deviation from a 1 m long straight edge in either plane should not exceed 10 mm
Navigation

question.title: Is plan or spine bracing loose or damaged?

answer.text: Drive in rack has plan bracing at the top of the racks and spine bracing at the rear. Plan and spine bracing must be free of damage and all bracing, including cables (where fitted) must at all times be clear of product

question.title: Are base plates damaged or twisted?

answer.text: Check base plates and fastenings for impact damage or twisting
Plates are often used with the base plates for levelling the rack. Check to ensure plates are correctly aligned

question.title: Are pallets in the rack in a safe and serviceable condition?

answer.text: The condition of the pallets and loads stored in the racks is important. Check pallets to ensure they are in good condition. Also check loads to ensure loads are stable on the pallet

Check that floor fixings are installed and are not damaged. Replace as required. If the floor fixing has been damaged, it is likely that the footplate will have also received damage and may need replacing. One bolt is normal in ea ch footplate, although back to back or double deep racking will commonly have bolts in the perimeter footplates only. Two or three bolts close together in a footplate may result in weakening of the floor

question.title: Are uprights vertical within acceptable limits?

answer.text: Check using sprit level for out - of - plumb both front - back and side - side
